description:
Wire route mode into the existing game component tree. This is the final integration bead that makes route mode playable end-to-end.

FILES TO MODIFY:

1. game/Game.tsx — MAIN BRANCHING POINT
   Currently, Game.tsx has a single code path:
   - useFeaturesInPlay → useGame → useGameStyling → useFeatureLabels → GMap with polygon features

   For route mode, NONE of these hooks apply. Add a conditional branch:
   ```tsx
   if (mode === 'route') {
     return <RouteGame />   // new component (see below)
   }
   // ... existing click/name mode code unchanged
   ```

   The route mode branch renders a completely separate component because route mode shares almost nothing with click/name mode (no polygons, no GeoJSON, no feature styles).

CREATE NEW FILE: game/route/RouteGame.tsx
   This is the top-level route mode component (equivalent to Game.tsx's body for click/name mode).

   ```tsx
   export const RouteGame = () => {
     const { seed, mode } = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.mapmemo.gameSettings)

     // Route mode hooks
     const routeState = useRouteMode(seed)
     const timer = useGameTimer({ isRunning: routeState.isGameActive && !routeState.isComplete })

     // Map interaction handlers
     const handleIntersectionClick = (intersection: RoadIntersection) => {
       routeState.handleIntersectionClick(intersection)
     }
     const handleDestinationClick = () => { /* mark complete */ }

     // Reset (play again)
     const handlePlayAgain = () => {
       dispatch(setGameSettings({ ...gameSettings, seed: randomSeed() }))
       routeState.reset()
       timer.resetTimer()
     }

     // Results screen
     if (routeState.isComplete) {
       return <RouteResults
         startAddress={routeState.startAddress}
         endAddress={routeState.endAddress}
         playerPath={routeState.path}
         elapsedMs={timer.elapsedMs}
         formattedTime={timer.formattedTime}
         onPlayAgain={handlePlayAgain}
       />
     }

     // Gameplay screen
     return (
       <section className={s_section}>
         <GMap
           spinUntilReady
           features={[]}         // no GeoJSON features for route mode
           onMapReady={handleMapReady}
         >
           {isMapReady && (
             <>
               <RouteGameHUD
                 routeState={routeState}
                 formattedTime={timer.formattedTime}
               />
               <GameSettingsButton />
             </>
           )}
         </GMap>
       </section>
     )
   }
   ```

   NOTE: GMap accepts features=[] for route mode. Route mode uses direct map objects (markers, polylines) managed by useRouteMapRendering, not the GMap data layer. The GMap component still provides the map instance and spinner.

2. game/Game.tsx — MODE BRANCH
   Add the import and early return for route mode at the top of the component:
   ```tsx
   const mode = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.mapmemo.gameSettings.mode)
   if (mode === 'route') return <RouteGame />
   ```
   This keeps the existing Game.tsx logic completely untouched for click/name mode.

3. game/route/RouteGameHUD.tsx — NEW FILE
   Route-specific HUD component. Simpler than the main GameHUD:
   - Timer (left) — same display as click/name mode
   - Prompt text (center):
     - isLoading → "Loading route..."
     - path.length === 0 → "Click an intersection to start navigating"
     - isDestinationReachable → "Click the destination to finish!"
     - otherwise → "Navigate towards [endAddress.name]"
   - No score (route mode doesn't have correct/incorrect counts during gameplay)
   - Same visual style as existing GameHUD (same Tailwind classes, same positioning)

IMPORTANT INTEGRATION NOTES:
- GMap.tsx currently wires up feature click/hover listeners. For route mode with features=[], these are effectively no-ops. Route mode click handling is done through AdvancedMarkerElement click listeners in useRouteMapRendering.
- The useRouteMapRendering hook needs the map instance from GMap's onMapReady callback. Wire this through state in RouteGame (same pattern as existing Game.tsx with isGMapReady).
- Timer starts when isGameActive becomes true (first intersection click) and stops when isComplete (destination reached).
- The seed-based reset (play again) generates a new seed and re-initializes. This may give the same addresses (only 2 in the list) but could swap A/B.
- GameSettingsButton should still work in route mode — it opens the settings panel where the player can change settings.
- Do NOT modify useGame.ts, useGameState.ts, useGameStyling.ts, or useFeaturesInPlay.ts. Route mode is a completely separate branch, not integrated into the existing hooks.

VALIDATION:
- Selecting route mode in settings and entering the game shows the route mode UI
- Spinner appears while loading, disappears when road data + addresses are ready
- HUD shows timer and prompt text
- Full gameplay loop works: see dots → click dots → route builds → reach destination → results screen
- Play again resets everything
- Settings button opens settings panel
- Switching back to click/name mode still works correctly
- No regressions in click/name mode behavior
